SENATE JOINT RESOLUTION 1053
By Campbell
A RESOLUTION to honor and congratulate Audrey Jean Glodé
Campbell on the occasion of her ninetieth
birthday.
WHEREAS, it is fitting that the members of this General Assembly should pay tribute to
those citizens who are celebrating special occasions in their estimable lives; and
WHEREAS, Audrey Jean Glodé Campbell celebrates her ninetieth birthday on May 3,
2026, a milestone commemorated as yet another precious souvenir of life's rich pageant; and
WHEREAS, Ms. Campbell, the beloved mother of our esteemed colleague Senator Heidi
Campbell, has lived an amazing life and has experienced firsthand the breadth and span of
American history; and
WHEREAS, born Audrey Jean Glodé in Chadron, Nebraska, on May 3, 1936, Audrey
Campbell grew up with a sister, Gretchen, and brother, Mike, and was a state champion flautist
during high school; and
WHEREAS, Ms. Campbell earned her Bachelor of Science degree from the University of
Nebraska Nursing School and her master's degree in education from the University of
Rochester in New York; she taught psychiatric nursing at the University of Rochester, the
University of Texas in Galveston, and the University of Colorado; and
WHEREAS, she became a resident of Nashville in 1970 and was married to renowned
Nashville cardiologist Bart Campbell for sixty-six years; the couple were blessed with three
children, Brent, Heather, and Senator Heidi Campbell; and
WHEREAS, Ms. Campbell is called "Nena" by her grandchildren—Kendrick, Hugh,
Connor, Blair, Campbell, and Atticus—and great-grandchildren—Margot and Audrey—and her
alter-ego-ideal, Imaginary Nena, is legendary, as there is no challenge she will not meet, no trip
she will not take, and no problem she cannot solve; and
SJR1053
016980
- 1 -

WHEREAS, she is also lovingly referred to as The Mega Horn (a.k.a. Old Flappy Lips)
by her family—there is no secret that she will keep; and
WHEREAS, a prolific author, Audrey Campbell is known as the Poet Laureate of Radnor
Lake; she has written and published multiple volumes of poetry, several children's books, and a
play—Our Family Troubles: The Legend of the Bell Witch, which had a highly successful run in
Nashville; and
WHEREAS, in the 1980s and 1990s, Ms. Campbell was a celebrated community
actress, performing as a lead in many productions, including Lu Ann Hampton Laverty
Oberlander, Sister Mary Ignatius Explains it All for You, and Antigone; she also served on the
board of the Nashville Children's Theater, and for more than a decade, she performed a weekly
story hour at the Green Hills Library for Nashville's pre-K children; and
WHEREAS, in addition to her talents as a writer and actress, Audrey Campbell has
exhibited great skill in creating stained-glass, pottery, and needlepoint, as well as with quilting
and illustrating; and
WHEREAS, her other abilities include making the best chocolate chip cookies, vegetable
soup, and Grandma Glodé cinnamon rolls, and rolling off a sailboat, into the brink, without
spilling her drink; and
WHEREAS, Audrey Campbell is a member in good standing with the United Peafowl
Association and has bred and beheld multiple varieties; she is also a bell-ringer at Westminster
Presbyterian Church in Nashville; and
WHEREAS, Ms. Campbell is a joy to be around and a blessing to all who have the good
fortune of knowing her, and she is a great friend to those in her Friday Morning Coffee Group,
Second Saturday Dinner Group, and Sunday Evening Salons; and
WHEREAS, as Ms. Campbell marks her ninetieth birthday, she remains a beloved
member of the Nashville community, admired for her faith, integrity, and enthusiasm for life; and
- 2 - 016980

WHEREAS, we wish to grasp this golden opportunity to specially recognize one of
Tennessee's most outstanding citizens on this very special occasion; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE SENATE OF THE ONE HUNDRED FOURTEENTH
GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE HOUSE OF
REPRESENTATIVES CONCURRING, that we recognize and honor Audrey Jean Glodé
Campbell on the celebration of her ninetieth birthday and extend to her our best wishes for
many happy returns of the day.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
